WEBVTT

00:00:03.031 --> 00:00:06.006
By January 1986, the Space Shuttle had

00:00:06.006 --> 00:00:08.825
flown twenty-four times. Each flight

00:00:08.825 --> 00:00:11.365
reinforced one idea the system worked.

00:00:12.367 --> 00:00:14.945
Across those flights, engineers documented

00:00:14.945 --> 00:00:18.497
O-ring damage. Erosion, blow-by hot gas

00:00:18.497 --> 00:00:20.922
past seals designed to hold.

00:00:21.763 --> 00:00:23.883
Low-temperature flights all showed

00:00:23.883 --> 00:00:26.209
distress. But each flight survived,

00:00:26.209 --> 00:00:28.074
and the warning lost force.

00:00:29.155 --> 00:00:30.739
Danger became a known condition.

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:33.382
A stop signal became a line item.

00:00:34.425 --> 00:00:36.466
The night before Challenger, engineers

00:00:36.466 --> 00:00:39.528
recommended against launch. The burden

00:00:39.528 --> 00:00:42.264
shifted instead of proving it safe to

00:00:42.264 --> 00:00:44.587
fly, they were asked to prove it

00:00:44.587 --> 00:00:48.150
was unsafe. On the coldest morning the

00:00:48.150 --> 00:00:49.804
program had ever faced, seventy-three

00:00:49.804 --> 00:00:52.088
seconds was all the physics needed.

00:00:52.149 --> 00:00:54.353
The warning was never missing.

00:00:55.295 --> 00:00:56.933
It had been made survivable for too

00:00:56.933 --> 00:01:00.527
long. Small causes, massive consequences.
